% ==============================================================
% ABSTRACT
% ==============================================================
\begin{abstract}
Conventional educational assessments present identical questions to every learner, failing to capture individual competency differences and providing limited diagnostic value. While Computerized Adaptive Testing (CAT) addresses this through dynamic difficulty adjustment, most CAT implementations depend on Item Response Theory (IRT) models that require large pre-calibrated item banks and offer little transparency into selection decisions. This paper presents an Adaptive Multi-Agent MCQ Difficulty Prediction System that replaces IRT-based computation with LLM-native reasoning by orchestrating three specialized agents through the CrewAI framework, each powered by Google Gemini 2.5 Flash. Adapting the Assess--Predict--Oversee--Transit (APOT) model proposed by Outay \textit{et al.}\ for competency building, the system deploys an MCQ Evaluator Agent for correctness determination, a Difficulty Predictor Agent for psychometric classification based on correctness and response time, and an Adaptive MCQ Overseer Agent that synthesizes both outputs to recommend the next question's difficulty level. A design-level analysis confirms complete coverage of all six correctness--difficulty transition combinations, logically consistent behavior across representative performance profiles, and a natural language audit trail for every adaptation decision. The proposed architecture demonstrates that prompt-engineered LLM agents can implement adaptive testing logic that is simultaneously interpretable, deployable without pre-calibrated item banks, and extensible through prompt modification alone.
\end{abstract}

\begin{IEEEkeywords}
adaptive assessment, multi-agent systems, large language models, MCQ difficulty prediction, CrewAI, computerized adaptive testing
\end{IEEEkeywords}

% ==============================================================
% I. INTRODUCTION
% ==============================================================
\section{Introduction}

Educational assessments serve as the primary mechanism through which learners demonstrate knowledge and instructors gauge comprehension. Yet the dominant testing paradigm remains static: every student receives the same set of questions at the same difficulty level, irrespective of prior performance, pace, or cognitive readiness. High-performing students encounter questions that fail to challenge them, while struggling students face items far beyond their current ability. Both extremes reduce the diagnostic value of the assessment and limit the actionable feedback available to educators~\cite{weiss2004}. Vygotsky's concept of the Zone of Proximal Development~\cite{vygotsky1978} established decades ago that effective learning occurs when tasks are calibrated just beyond a learner's current capability---a principle that static assessments structurally violate.

Computerized Adaptive Testing (CAT) emerged to address this gap by selecting questions dynamically based on a running estimate of student ability~\cite{lord1980}. The statistical backbone of most CAT systems is Item Response Theory (IRT), which models the probability of a correct response as a function of student ability and item parameters such as difficulty, discrimination, and guessing probability~\cite{hambleton1985}. While statistically rigorous, IRT imposes substantial practical barriers. Each item must be pre-calibrated through large-scale pilot administrations, and the resulting parameter estimates are population-dependent, making cross-context reuse unreliable. The probabilistic models behind IRT are opaque to non-statisticians, which erodes instructor trust in formative settings where understanding \textit{why} a question was selected matters as much as \textit{which} question was selected~\cite{mislevy2003}.

Recent advances in Large Language Models (LLMs) open an alternative pathway. Rather than computing numerical ability estimates and matching them against item parameters, LLM-powered agents can reason directly over observable performance signals---answer correctness and response time---and apply adaptation rules expressed in natural language. This approach encodes psychometric heuristics into agent prompts instead of statistical formulas, producing decisions that are inherently interpretable and modifiable without retraining or re-calibration. Multi-agent orchestration frameworks such as CrewAI and AutoGen~\cite{liang2023} make it feasible to decompose the adaptation task across specialized agents, each with a well-defined role, mirroring the staged reasoning found in established competency-building models.

Outay \textit{et al.}~\cite{outay2024} proposed a Multi-Agent System (MAS) framework for competency building organized around the recursive APOT model---Assess, Predict, Oversee, Transit. Their framework introduces specialized agents including the Learning Style Assessment Agent (LSAA), the Stage of Learning Prediction Agent (SoLPA), the Stage of Learning Monitoring Agent (SoLMA), and the Stage of Learning Transition Agent (SoLTA), which collaboratively compute a Learning Index and Competency Index to track learner progress. While their work provides a rigorous multi-agent foundation, it targets augmented reality (AR)-based vocational training and relies on quantitative KPI metrics with deterministic index computations. Our system adapts the APOT model's cyclic stage philosophy into a fully LLM-driven, question-based adaptive testing context where all reasoning is performed by language model agents.

This paper makes the following contributions:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item A three-agent CrewAI pipeline powered by Google Gemini 2.5 Flash that replaces formula-driven IRT scoring with LLM-native contextual reasoning for adaptive MCQ difficulty prediction.
    \item An adaptation of the APOT model~\cite{outay2024}---originally designed for AR-based vocational training with agents such as LSAA, SoLPA, SoLMA, and SoLTA---to a question-level adaptive testing context where each APOT phase maps to a specialized LLM agent.
    \item A psychometric reasoning mechanism embedded in agent prompts that classifies question difficulty from correctness and response time without IRT parameters.
    \item A structured output and fallback parsing design that ensures graceful degradation under LLM output variability.
    \item A design-level analysis demonstrating complete adaptive rule coverage, consistent behavioral traces, and pipeline integrity across the agent collaboration.
\end{enumerate}

The remainder of this paper is organized as follows. Section~II reviews related work in multi-agent educational systems, computerized adaptive testing, and LLM-augmented assessment. Section~III describes the system architecture and its relationship to the APOT model. Section~IV details the multi-agent framework design. Section~V presents the methodology including input representation, agent specification, and output parsing. Section~VI provides a system analysis with adaptive rule coverage and behavioral trace evaluation. Section~VII concludes with a summary and directions for future work.

