% II. RELATED WORK
% ==============================================================
\section{Related Work}

\subsection{Multi-Agent Systems in Education}

Multi-Agent Systems have been applied to educational technology for over two decades, motivated by the natural decomposition of learning support into distinct collaborative roles~\cite{wooldridge2009}. Conati \textit{et al.}~\cite{conati2002} demonstrated early on that Bayesian student models could be distributed across multiple agents to manage uncertainty in learner states. More recently, Outay \textit{et al.}~\cite{outay2024} proposed the APOT (Assess--Predict--Oversee--Transit) model, a recursive multi-agent framework for competency building in smart learning environments. Their system deploys several specialized agents: the Learning Style Assessment Agent (LSAA) identifies individual learning preferences, the Stage of Learning Prediction Agent (SoLPA) forecasts learner trajectories, the Stage of Learning Monitoring Agent (SoLMA) tracks real-time progress against competency targets, and the Stage of Learning Transition Agent (SoLTA) manages transitions between learning stages based on accumulated performance data. Together, these agents compute a Learning Index (LI) and Competency Index (CI) to guide learner progression through competency stages.

The APOT framework's strength lies in its clear separation of assessment, prediction, oversight, and transition responsibilities across agents. However, the system was designed for AR-based vocational training environments involving guided instruction sequences, and its agents rely on quantitative KPI metrics and deterministic index formulas. Our work preserves the APOT model's multi-agent collaboration philosophy and cyclic stage structure while replacing the deterministic computations with LLM-based reasoning and redirecting the application from guided training to question-based adaptive assessment.

\subsection{Computerized Adaptive Testing and IRT Limitations}

CAT has been studied extensively since the foundational work of Lord~\cite{lord1980} and represents the standard approach to personalized assessment. IRT models---including the one-parameter (Rasch), two-parameter, and three-parameter logistic models---provide the statistical machinery for estimating student ability and selecting items that maximize measurement precision at the current ability estimate~\cite{hambleton1985}. Weiss~\cite{weiss2004} summarized the effectiveness of CAT for efficient measurement but also noted its dependence on well-calibrated item banks.

The practical limitations of IRT are well documented. Constructing a calibrated item bank requires pilot testing with hundreds or thousands of examinees per item, making it prohibitively expensive for small-scale or rapidly evolving educational contexts. Item parameters are sample-dependent, meaning a bank calibrated on one population may not transfer reliably to another. The mathematical opacity of IRT models---where item selection follows maximum information criteria computed from logistic functions---makes it difficult for educators to understand or override selection decisions in formative contexts~\cite{mislevy2003}. Our approach sidesteps these limitations entirely by generating questions on-the-fly via LLM prompts and delegating difficulty classification to agents that reason in natural language over correctness and time, eliminating the need for any pre-calibrated item bank.

\subsection{LLM-Augmented Assessment Frameworks}

The integration of Large Language Models into educational systems has accelerated across multiple fronts. Chen \textit{et al.}~\cite{chen2023} surveyed LLM applications in education, identifying feedback generation, content creation, and tutoring as primary use cases. Frameworks such as AutoGen~\cite{liang2023} enable multi-agent conversations where LLM-powered agents collaborate on complex tasks, and CrewAI provides a role-based agent orchestration layer with explicit task dependencies and context passing.

Bloom's taxonomy~\cite{bloom1956} supplies the cognitive hierarchy that informs how question difficulty relates to learner ability, and our three-level difficulty scheme (Easy, Medium, Hard) aligns with the lower, intermediate, and higher cognitive strata of this taxonomy. Reinforcement learning approaches~\cite{sutton2018} have also been explored for adaptive question selection, but they require extensive interaction histories for policy training and lack the interpretability that prompt-based agents provide.

A critical gap in the existing literature is the absence of systems that delegate the \textit{full} adaptive assessment pipeline---correctness evaluation, difficulty classification, and adaptation decision---to LLM agents. Prior hybrid systems typically restrict LLMs to feedback generation or content creation while retaining formula-based scoring and IRT-driven item selection for the core adaptation logic. Our system addresses this gap by entrusting all three assessment stages to prompt-engineered LLM agents, demonstrating that the reasoning capabilities of modern language models are sufficient to implement psychometric adaptation logic that was previously the exclusive domain of statistical models.

