% III. SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE
% ==============================================================
\section{System Architecture}

\subsection{Per-Question Adaptive Loop}

The system follows a per-question adaptive loop that triggers on every student response. When a student submits an answer, the system captures the selected option and the elapsed response time. These two observable signals, along with the question text and correct answer, are passed to the CrewAI pipeline. Three agents execute sequentially: the MCQ Evaluator Agent determines whether the answer is correct, the Difficulty Predictor Agent classifies the current question's difficulty, and the Adaptive MCQ Overseer Agent synthesizes both outputs to produce the recommended difficulty for the next question. The loop then generates a new question at the recommended difficulty level using Google Gemini 2.5 Flash, and the cycle repeats. This architecture ensures that every question in the session reflects the student's demonstrated performance on the immediately preceding item.

\subsection{Three-Layer Architecture}

The system is organized into three layers with clearly separated responsibilities:

The \textbf{Presentation Layer} manages the student-facing interface, including question display, answer selection, a countdown timer enforcing a 20-minute session limit, and a fullscreen integrity gate that constrains the testing environment. Answer submissions and timing data are transmitted to the backend via asynchronous HTTP requests.

The \textbf{Orchestration Layer} coordinates the CrewAI agent pipeline. It receives the student's response data, constructs the structured input string, triggers sequential agent execution, parses the Overseer Agent's output, and invokes on-the-fly question generation at the determined difficulty level. A synchronous rule-based fallback provides immediate difficulty decisions for the next question while the full agent pipeline runs asynchronously in a background thread, decoupling UI responsiveness from LLM latency.

The \textbf{Analytics Layer} encompasses the three CrewAI agents themselves. Each agent applies its specialized reasoning---correctness verification, psychometric difficulty classification, or adaptive rule application---through LLM inference over structured prompts. Agent outputs are persisted to a relational database for auditing and longitudinal analysis.

\subsection{APOT Phase Mapping}

The original APOT model proposed by Outay \textit{et al.}~\cite{outay2024} organizes competency building into four recursive stages: Assess, Predict, Oversee, and Transit. In their framework, these stages are managed by agents such as the Learning Style Assessment Agent (LSAA), the Stage of Learning Prediction Agent (SoLPA), the Stage of Learning Monitoring Agent (SoLMA), and the Stage of Learning Transition Agent (SoLTA), each operating over quantitative KPIs and deterministic index formulas.

Our system maps the APOT stages to LLM-driven agents operating at the granularity of individual questions rather than learning sessions. The \textit{Assess} stage corresponds to the MCQ Evaluator Agent, which determines answer correctness---analogous to the role of SoLMA in monitoring learning outcomes. The \textit{Predict} stage maps to the Difficulty Predictor Agent, which classifies question difficulty using psychometric heuristics---paralleling SoLPA's prediction function but replacing quantitative indices with LLM reasoning. The \textit{Oversee} and \textit{Transit} stages are both handled by the Adaptive MCQ Overseer Agent, which reviews the combined analysis and produces the transition recommendation---a role that synthesizes the oversight of SoLMA with the transition management of SoLTA. Fig.~\ref{fig:pipeline} illustrates the complete three-agent pipeline.

