% ==============================================================
% IV. MULTI-AGENT FRAMEWORK
% ==============================================================
\section{Multi-Agent Framework}

All three agents are implemented using the CrewAI framework's \texttt{Agent} class, with behavior governed by three natural language fields: \texttt{role}, \texttt{goal}, and \texttt{backstory}. Each agent is powered by Google Gemini 2.5 Flash via the CrewAI LLM interface, configured with a temperature of 0.7 to balance consistency with contextual flexibility.

\subsection{MCQ Evaluator Agent}

The MCQ Evaluator Agent serves as the entry point of the pipeline and corresponds to the \textit{Assess} phase of the APOT model. Its role is defined as ``MCQ Evaluator Agent'' with the goal of accurately determining whether a student's selected answer is correct or incorrect. The agent's backstory characterizes it as a strict and fair MCQ examiner whose sole function is to compare the student's answer against the correct option.

The agent receives a structured input block containing four fields: the question text, the correct answer, the student's selected answer, and the response time in seconds. Its task specifies an expected output of a binary correctness verdict accompanied by a one-line explanation. The agent is configured with \texttt{allow\_delegation=False} to prevent it from deferring this factual judgment to other agents, ensuring that correctness determination remains isolated from difficulty reasoning.

\subsection{Difficulty Predictor Agent}

The Difficulty Predictor Agent corresponds to the \textit{Predict} phase of the APOT model and is responsible for classifying the difficulty of the current question into one of three levels: Easy, Medium, or Hard. Its backstory encodes a psychometric heuristic grounded in the relationship between response time, correctness, and item difficulty: a fast and correct response signals an Easy question, a slow but correct response indicates a Medium question, and an incorrect response---regardless of time---signals a Hard question.

This heuristic reflects established findings in adaptive testing literature~\cite{weiss2004} that response time, in conjunction with correctness, serves as a behavioral proxy for item difficulty. The agent's approach parallels the prediction function of the Stage of Learning Prediction Agent (SoLPA) in the original APOT framework~\cite{outay2024}, but replaces SoLPA's quantitative index computation with natural language reasoning. No hard-coded time thresholds are defined; the agent applies the heuristic contextually based on the response time value provided. The expected output is a difficulty classification with supporting reasoning. Like the Evaluator, the Predictor is configured with \texttt{allow\_delegation=False}.

\subsection{Adaptive MCQ Overseer Agent}

The Adaptive MCQ Overseer Agent is the most complex component of the pipeline, serving both the \textit{Oversee} and \textit{Transit} functions of the APOT model. It receives the outputs of both preceding agents as context through CrewAI's task dependency mechanism and synthesizes them to produce two decisions: a confirmed difficulty classification for the current question and a recommended difficulty level for the next question.

The agent's backstory encodes an explicit bidirectional adaptive rule set. For correct answers, the rules specify progressive escalation: Easy transitions to Medium, Medium advances to Hard, and Hard remains at Hard or steps down to Medium to consolidate mastery. For incorrect answers, the rules specify stepwise de-escalation: Hard transitions to Medium, Medium drops to Easy, and Easy remains at Easy to reinforce foundational skills. These rules are grounded in Vygotsky's Zone of Proximal Development~\cite{vygotsky1978}, maintaining the learner at the boundary of their current ability, and align with the progressive cognitive demands described in Bloom's taxonomy~\cite{bloom1956}.

The Overseer Agent is the only agent configured with \texttt{allow\_delegation=True}, enabling it to request clarification from prior agents if needed. Its task description enforces a structured output format:

\begin{verbatim}
Questions Difficulty: [Easy/Medium/Hard]
Next Question Difficulty: [Easy/Medium/Hard]
Reasoning: [explanation]
Recommendation: [additional actions]
\end{verbatim}

This structured format enables reliable programmatic parsing while preserving the natural language reasoning chain for audit purposes.

\subsection{CrewAI Orchestration}

The three agents are assembled into a CrewAI \texttt{Crew} with the following configuration: \texttt{process=Process.sequential} ensures deterministic execution order; \texttt{memory=False} enforces stateless per-question operation, preventing cross-question information leakage; and \texttt{max\_rpm=10} enforces API rate compliance to prevent throttling under concurrent usage. Three corresponding \texttt{Task} objects define each agent's inputs and expected outputs. Task~3 (assigned to the Overseer Agent) explicitly declares \texttt{context=[task1, task2]}, granting it access to the full output of both the Evaluator and the Predictor before rendering its decision. The \texttt{crew.kickoff()} method executes the complete pipeline and returns the Overseer Agent's final output as a string for downstream parsing.

