\subsection{Agent Role Separation and Pipeline Integrity}

The three-agent design enforces a strict separation of concerns that mirrors the APOT model's staged reasoning~\cite{outay2024}. The Evaluator Agent handles only factual correctness comparison, with no access to difficulty reasoning or adaptation rules. The Predictor Agent applies psychometric heuristics to classify the current question's difficulty, without knowledge of the adaptive transition logic. Only the Overseer Agent integrates correctness, predicted difficulty, and the adaptive rule set to produce transition recommendations. This staged decomposition prevents the conflation of concerns that would arise if a single agent were tasked with the entire pipeline, and makes each agent's reasoning independently verifiable.

