\subsection{LLM-Native Adaptation vs.\ Formula-Based Approaches}

Delegating difficulty reasoning to LLM agents rather than deterministic formulas produces several advantages. First, adaptation rules are expressed and modified entirely in natural language. Adjusting the escalation policy requires editing the Overseer Agent's backstory text, not rewriting scoring code or retraining a statistical model. Second, the agents can incorporate contextual nuance that rigid numeric formulas cannot express---recognizing, for example, borderline cases where response time falls near implicit thresholds. Third, the complete reasoning chain is available in the agent's output, providing educators with a natural language explanation for every difficulty decision. This directly supports the explainability goals articulated in the APOT framework~\cite{outay2024}. Fourth, eliminating IRT pre-calibration parameters makes the system deployable in any subject domain without prior item bank construction~\cite{hambleton1985}; questions are generated on-the-fly by Gemini 2.5 Flash at the specified difficulty level.

\subsection{Limitations and Trade-offs}

The primary trade-off is non-determinism inherent in LLM outputs. Identical inputs may occasionally produce slightly different difficulty classifications or reasoning chains across executions. The system mitigates this through three mechanisms: the structured output format enforced in the Overseer Agent's task description, the keyword-based parsing logic that extracts only the required fields from potentially verbose responses, and the default-to-Medium fallback that ensures defined behavior when parsing fails.

A second limitation is latency. The three-agent pipeline requires three sequential LLM inference calls, which can introduce perceptible delays. The dual-layer architecture---synchronous rule-based fallback for immediate UI response, asynchronous agent pipeline for persistent analysis---addresses this by decoupling the student experience from the full pipeline's execution time.

A third consideration is the absence of empirical validation with human participants. The analysis presented here is design-level, examining logical consistency and rule coverage rather than statistical agreement with expert difficulty judgments. Empirical evaluation remains essential future work and is discussed in Section~VII.

