% VII. CONCLUSION AND FUTURE WORK
% ==============================================================
\section{Conclusion and Future Work}

This paper presented an Adaptive Multi-Agent MCQ Difficulty Prediction System that operationalizes the APOT framework~\cite{outay2024}---with its specialized agents LSAA, SoLPA, SoLMA, and SoLTA---in a fully LLM-driven, question-based adaptive testing context. By deploying three CrewAI agents powered by Google Gemini 2.5 Flash, the system replaces IRT pre-calibration and deterministic scoring formulas with prompt-engineered LLM reasoning over answer correctness and response time.

The design-level analysis confirms that the three-agent pipeline achieves complete coverage of the six-state adaptive transition space, logically consistent behavior across representative performance scenarios, and a natural language audit trail for every difficulty decision. These results demonstrate that LLM-native multi-agent architectures can implement adaptive testing logic that is simultaneously interpretable, deployable without pre-calibrated item banks, and extensible through prompt modification.

Future work will pursue the following directions: (1)~conducting user studies with diverse student populations to empirically validate LLM-predicted difficulty labels against expert annotations; (2)~extending the system to multi-domain assessments spanning quantitative, verbal, and reasoning tasks with domain-specific agent prompts; (3)~integrating session-level memory into the CrewAI pipeline to enable cross-question performance tracking and long-horizon difficulty planning; (4)~exploring prompt optimization and few-shot calibration techniques to reduce LLM output variability; (5)~comparing LLM-based adaptation decisions against IRT-based ground truth on standardized item banks to quantify agreement rates and identify systematic biases; and (6)~developing a concurrent multi-user deployment with real-time difficulty dashboards for instructors.

